==English==
[[Image:Dagger_India_Louvre_MR13434.jpg|thumb|An ornamental dagger]]

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} ''[[dague]]'', from Old Provencal ''daga'', from Germanic (cf. German ''Degen'', Old Norse ''dage'').

===Pronunciation===
* {{rhymes|æɡə(r)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|weapon}}  A [[stab]]bing [[weapon]], similar to a [[sword]] but with a short, [[double-edged]] [[blade]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Wives}}, Act I, Scene I, line 282.
#*: I bruised my shin th’ other day with playing at sword and '''dagger''' with a master of fence; ...
#* '''1786''', [[w:Francis Grose|Francis Grose]], ''A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons'', page 34.
#*: The '''dagger''', under the title cultellum and misericorde, has been the constant companion of the sword, at least from the days of Edward I. and is mentioned in the statute of Winchester.
# A text [[character]] ('''†''') that is used for [[footnote]]s, to signify [[death]], and to express the mathematical application of Hermitian conjugacy.

